05036nmm a2200949Ia 9781501728815DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182002nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017288157 a10.7591/97815017288152doi  a(DE-B1597)515472  a(OCoLC)1088910853  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a347.747/0162211 aMerwick, Donna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeath of a Notary :bConquest and Change in Colonial New York /cDonna Merwick. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b33 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"He was the only one. He was the only man to have committed suicide in the town's seventeenth-century history." So begins Donna Merwick's fascinating tale of a Dutch notary who ended his life in his adopted community of Albany. In a major feat of historical reconstruction, she introduces us to Adriaen Janse van Ilpendam and the long-forgotten world he inhabited in Holland's North American colony. Her powerful narrative will make readers care for this quiet and studious man, an "ordinary" settler for whom the clash of empires brought tragedy.Like so many of his fellow countrymen, Janse left his Dutch homeland as a young adult to try his luck in New Netherland. After spending a few years on Manhattan Island, he moved on to the fur trading settlement today known as Albany. Merwick traces his journey to a new continent and re-creates the satisfying existence this respected burgher enjoyed with his wife in the bustling town. As a notary Janse was, in the author's words, "surrounded by stories, those he listened to and recorded, the hundreds he archived in a chest or trunk." His familiar life was turned upside down by the British conquest of the colony. Merwick recounts the changes brought about by the new rulers and imagines the despair Janse must have felt when English, a language he had never learned, replaced his native tongue in official transactions. In any military adventure, truth is alleged to be the first casualty. Merwick offers a poignant reminder that the first casualties are in fact people. As much a musing on what history obscures as what it reveals, her book is a superior work by a master practitioner of her craft.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aNotarieszNew York (State)vBiography. 0aNotarieszNew York (State)xHistory. 4aNew York History. 4aU.S. History.  a17th century american history .  a17th century history .  a17th-century Albany.  aAdriaen Janse van Ilpendam.  aAmerican historians.  aColonial social history.  aDutch in the New World.  aDutch-English influence in New York.  aamerican colonial period .  aamerican colonies.  aamerican history studies .  abeverwijck.  abiography of colonists.  abiography of new yorker.  acolonial new york .  acolonial notaries .  acolonial period history .  adaily life in the new colony.  adutch americans .  adutch colony .  agraduate history collections.  agraduate history.  ahistorians .  ahistorical notaries .  ahistory .  ahistory of albany new york .  ahistory of new york .  amanhatans .  anew ablanij.  anew england history .  anew york state history .  anieuw albanij in america.  anotaries as archivists.  anotaries history .08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172881540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501728815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501728815/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d